====See also====
{{Latn-script}}
===Etymology 2===
The variable name comes from usage in Spain, as up to the 16th century ⟨x⟩ had the sound value /ʃ/ in {{bor|mul|es|-}}, so was used to transcribe {{der|mul|ar|ش}} used for the purpose of a variable as an abbreviation of {{m|ar|شَيْء|t=thing}}.<ref>{{R:mul:Lagarde:1882}}</ref> Its sound value is since then /x/ which explains the decision {{w|History of the International Phonetic Alphabet|made}} in the circle of the {{w|International Phonetic Association}} to assign this character to the voiceless velar fricative. Compare {{noncog|en|hickey|t=an object whose name is not recalled; bruise-like mark made during petting by pressing the mouth to the skin}} for the development of the sense of a communicated kiss.
