===Etymology 3===
The {{w|multiplication sign}} is an arbitrary notation developed in the early 17th century.
====Symbol====
{{head|mul|symbol}}
# {{alternative spelling of |mul|×}}
#: {{ux|en|Dimensions: 1280'''x'''720}}
#: {{ux|en|3'''x''' as much as usual}}
#* '''2017''', Karin Loose, ''Gesunde Lebensführung - Gewusst wie!?: Ernährung + Bewegung + Psyche'', BookRix ({{ISBN|9783743825529}})"
#*: Nebenzahlreichen sekundären Pflanzenstoffen enthält Moringa: 2'''x''' so viel Proteine wie Soja [...]
=====Usage notes=====
Using {{m|en|x}} (in upper- or lower-case, italicized or not, and sometimes rotated 90 degrees) to indicate multiplication was common in 17th-century mathematical texts.<ref>{{cite-journal|last=Cajori|first=Florian|title=The Cross X as a Symbol for Multiplication|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/094363c0|journal=Nature|volume=94|year=1914|month=December|pages=363–364|doi=10.1038/094363c0}}</ref> Today, this usage is considered poor typography, but it is nevertheless common because computer keyboards lack a × key.
=====References=====
<references/>
===Etymology 4===
[[File:DOnaTREN.jpg|thumb|right|A [[CD-R]] claiming '''52X''' speed.|upright=1.35]]
[[File:Maxell Branded DVD-R.JPG|thumb|right|A [[DVD-R]] claiming '''8x''' speed.|upright=1.35]]
Originates in given multiples of the speeds specified in the original CD and DVD standards, then, by reason of the actual unit being without name but just implied by the multiplication sign, reinterpreted as or used as if a unit, considering also that data transfer speed is ''variable'', so that now, bolstered by stylization of the sign in the marketing of manufacturers, either spelling, with the multiplication sign or with the ex borrowed from the iconic mathematical variable sign, seems correct.
====Symbol====
{{head|mul|symbol}}
# {{lb|mul|computing}} A [[unit]] of [[transfer rate]] of [[CD]] drives, equal to 150 [[KiB]] per second.
# {{lb|mul|computing}} A [[unit]] of [[transfer rate]] of [[DVD]] drives, equal 1.32 [[MiB]] per second.
====Further reading====
* {{cite-web|url=https://kb.iu.edu/d/adme|work=Indiana University: University Information Technology Services Knowledge Base|title=What is meant by the speed of a CD or DVD drive?|date=2018-01-18}}
* {{pedia|lang=en|Optical disc drive#Rotational mechanism}}
* {{pedia|lang=en|CD and DVD writing speed}}
